Yakiniku Don (焼肉丼) — makes 4 bowls
Beef & Marinade
	∙	1½ lbs beef (rib-eye or chuck, sliced thin against the grain — freeze 30 min for easier slicing)
	∙	¼ cup soy sauce
	∙	2 tbsp mirin
	∙	1 tbsp sake (or dry sherry)
	∙	1 tbsp toasted sesame oil
	∙	1 tbsp brown sugar
	∙	1 tbsp gochujang (optional — adds a subtle warmth)
	∙	4 cloves garlic, grated
	∙	1 tbsp fresh ginger, grated
	∙	1 tsp black pepper
Rice
	∙	2 cups short-grain Japanese rice (Koshihikari if you can find it)
	∙	Water per your rice cooker or package directions
	∙	1 tbsp rice vinegar (toss through after cooking — subtle but makes a difference)
Toppings
	∙	4 eggs (soft-boiled 6.5 min or fried runny)
	∙	4 green onions, thinly sliced
	∙	1 tbsp toasted sesame seeds
	∙	Kewpie mayo (a drizzle)
	∙	Pickled cucumber or kimchi on the side
	∙	Shichimi togarashi (Japanese seven spice)
Yakiniku Tare (glaze/sauce)
	∙	3 tbsp soy sauce
	∙	2 tbsp mirin
	∙	1 tbsp sake
	∙	1 tbsp brown sugar
	∙	1 tsp toasted sesame oil
	∙	1 clove garlic, grated
Combine in a small saucepan, simmer 3–4 minutes until slightly thickened. Set aside.
Instructions
	1.	Marinate. Toss sliced beef with all marinade ingredients. Let sit at least 30 minutes at room temp, or up to overnight in the fridge. The longer the better.
	2.	Cook rice. Rinse until water runs clear (3–4 rinses). Cook however you normally do. Once done, gently fold in the rice vinegar and keep covered.
	3.	Prep eggs. For soft-boiled: bring water to a rolling boil, lower eggs in gently, cook exactly 6 minutes 30 seconds, then straight into an ice bath. Peel when cool. For fried: cook in butter over medium, basting the whites, keeping the yolk runny.
	4.	Sear the beef. This is the most important step. Get a cast iron or carbon steel pan ripping hot — smoking hot. A little neutral oil (avocado or vegetable). Cook beef in small batches, single layer, don’t crowd the pan. You want hard caramelization, not steaming. About 1–2 minutes per side. The sugars in the marinade will char and create that yakiniku flavor. Resist the urge to move the beef around.
	5.	Assemble. Big scoop of rice in a bowl, press it down slightly. Pile the seared beef on one side. Nestle a halved soft-boiled egg next to it. Drizzle the tare sauce over the beef. Top with green onions, sesame seeds, a zigzag of Kewpie, and a shake of shichimi togarashi.
What makes this hit different: The double sauce approach — the marinade flavors the beef deeply, then the tare glaze adds a fresh layer of sweet-savory shine on top. The screaming hot pan is non-negotiable; that char is the whole point of yakiniku. And Koshihikari rice is stickier and slightly sweet, which is the perfect base for all those bold flavors.​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​